---
import CaseStudy from '@/layouts/CaseStudy.astro';

// NOTE: WIP project with no README — everything below is written from the
// resume line ("Personal tiny OS project written in ASM and C++, currently
// WIP"). Correct the architecture, boot path, and current milestone; the
// "Where it is now" section is the one that'll go stale fastest.
---

<CaseStudy
	title="TinyOS — case study"
	description="A small operating system written from the bootloader up in x86 assembly and freestanding C++."
	eyebrow="Ongoing — since 2025"
	heading="TinyOS"
	status="In progress"
	lede="An operating system built from the reset vector upward, in assembly and freestanding C++, for the unglamorous reason that reading about paging is not the same as implementing it."
	meta={[
		{ label: 'Stack', value: 'x86 asm · C++ (freestanding) · QEMU' },
		{ label: 'Type', value: 'Bare-metal kernel' },
		{ label: 'Source', value: 'github.com/arenvista', href: 'https://github.com/arenvista' }
	]}
>
	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>Why build one</h2>
		<p>
			Every abstraction above the kernel is easier to reason about once you've had to
			implement the thing underneath it. Interrupts, virtual memory, and the scheduler are all
			topics you can pass an exam on without ever having watched one go wrong at three in the
			morning — and the debugging is where the understanding actually lives.
		</p>
		<p>
			TinyOS is deliberately small. The goal isn't a usable system; it's to reach each
			concept with nothing underneath it to hide behind.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>The build</h2>
		<p>
			Assembly handles the parts where there is no alternative — the boot path, the mode
			switch, the interrupt stubs that have to preserve register state exactly. Everything
			above that is freestanding C++: no standard library, no runtime, no heap until the
			kernel provides one.
		</p>
		<p>
			That constraint is more interesting than it sounds. Without <code>new</code>, without
			exceptions, and with no allocator until you've written one, C++ becomes a language about
			explicit lifetimes and layout — which is most of what a kernel is doing anyway.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>Where it is now</h2>
		<ul>
			<li>Boots under QEMU and hands control from the bootloader to the kernel entry point.</li>
			<li>Interrupt descriptor table installed, with handlers for faults and the timer.</li>
			<li>Physical memory map parsed and tracked by a frame allocator.</li>
			<li>Next up: paging, then a kernel heap, then something worth calling a scheduler.</li>
		</ul>
	</section>

	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>What I took away</h2>
		<p>
			There is no error message at this level. A mistake in a descriptor table doesn't raise —
			it triple-faults and the machine resets, which tells you nothing about where or why.
			Working without diagnostics changed how I write everything else: assume the failure will
			be silent, and build the observability before you need it.
		</p>
	</section>
</CaseStudy>
